Review: Nothing is more exhilarating than a revenge film. Female Prisoner #701 is no exception. The plot meanders, sure, with some detours feeling entirely unnecessary, but that hardly matters. Even basic conversations are elevated by expressive performances, and energetic zoom-ins bring life to a (mostly) drab prison setting. I've really been sleeping on the MCU. I don't actively avoid it, and I've actually been planning to marathon it all for a long time now. The only problem is that it's a lot, and I don't resonate with superhero stories. I fear it would ultimately turn into a checklist, which is neither enjoyable nor productive. Every performance in Francisca is wonderfully stagnant. For a film supposedly about a romance, everyone comes off as heartless--except maybe Francisca herself, who suffers a Tolstoyan fate for the mistake of falling in love.
There are so many sexual innuendos in this. I was not expecting that at all

This is an incredibly odd movie. On one hand, letting Ari Aster make a pseudo-odyssean dark comedy with a 35 million dollar budget was such a bad idea. On the other hand... that's an idea so bad, it might actually be good.

I had such high expectations for this... somehow, An Cailín Ciúin surpassed them all.Everything, and I mean everything, about this film is beautiful. The dirt roads, the cows, the wallpaper, the sea... the trains, the clothes, the well. Every scene is acted and shot with a gentle majesty, letting you absorb it at your own pace. I adore the stillness, the silence, present in even the most kinetic scenes.It's no surprise I connected to this story. I've always…

Review: "This burden you carry, you might let me carry it too... I believe in you."As a western written and scored by Nick Cave, this is as poetic and morose as you'd expect. Trilogy ranking: 2>3>1The first Pusher film followed Frank, a posturing wannabe gangster who doesn't realize how screwed he is until it's far too late. Pusher 2 was about Tonny, a recently released convict who reenters a life of crime at his father's behest, and later decides that life isn't for him.
